# Translation Management System - Cursor Rules

## Package Management
- Always use the latest stable versions of Next.js packages
- Check for latest versions before installing: `npm outdated`
- Prefer Next.js 15+ with App Router
- Use latest React 19+ if compatible
- Always check package.json for latest versions before adding dependencies

## Shadcn UI Components
- **ALWAYS use the Shadcn MCP server** when adding/updating components
- Use `mcp_shadcn_search_items_in_registries` to find components
- Use `mcp_shadcn_get_add_command_for_items` to get installation commands
- Use `mcp_shadcn_view_items_in_registries` to view component details
- Use `mcp_shadcn_get_item_examples_from_registries` for usage examples
- Prefer Shadcn components over custom implementations
- Keep components up-to-date with latest Shadcn versions
- Use `mcp_shadcn_get_audit_checklist` after creating new components

## Context7 Integration
- Use Context7 MCP server for library documentation when:
  - Implementing complex features (NextAuth, Drizzle, etc.)
  - Need API reference or code examples
  - Learning new library patterns
- Use `mcp_context7_resolve-library-id` to find library IDs
- Use `mcp_context7_get-library-docs` for documentation with mode='code' for API references

## UX/UI Principles
- **Simplest possible UX**: Minimize clicks, reduce cognitive load
- **Aesthetically very modern**: Clean, minimal design with smooth animations
- Use consistent spacing and typography
- Implement micro-interactions for better feedback
- Mobile-first responsive design
- Accessibility: ARIA labels, keyboard navigation, focus states
- Use Shadcn UI's built-in accessibility features

## Icons & Typography
- **Icons**: Use bright, modern icon sets:
  - Primary: Lucide React (bright and modern, already included)
  - Alternative: Google Material Symbols if needed
  - Consider: Heroicons, Tabler Icons for variety
- **Typography**: 
  - Use Google Fonts for headings: Inter, Poppins, or Geist (Next.js default)
  - System fonts for body text (Inter, system-ui)
  - Ensure good contrast in both dark/light modes
  - Use font-display: swap for performance

## Code Quality
- Use TypeScript strictly (no `any` types, use `unknown` if needed)
- Follow Next.js 15+ best practices
- Use Server Components by default, Client Components only when needed ('use client')
- Implement proper error boundaries
- Use Zod for validation
- Follow consistent naming conventions:
  - camelCase for variables and functions
  - PascalCase for components
  - UPPER_SNAKE_CASE for constants
  - kebab-case for file names (except components)
- **ALWAYS use current date/time**: Never use dates from training data
  - Use `date` command or JavaScript `new Date()` to get current date
  - Format dates as: "Month Year" (e.g., "January 2025")
  - For timestamps, use ISO format or current system time
  - When updating documentation dates, always use the actual current date

## Component Patterns
- Use Shadcn UI components as base, customize with Tailwind
- Keep components small and focused (single responsibility)
- Use composition over configuration
- Prefer server actions over API routes when possible
- Use React Server Components for data fetching

## Styling
- Use Tailwind CSS utility classes
- Use CSS variables for theming (Shadcn pattern)
- Support both dark and light modes
- Use consistent color palette from Shadcn theme
- Add smooth transitions for theme changes

## Performance
- Optimize images (use Next.js Image component)
- Use dynamic imports for heavy components
- Implement proper loading states
- Use React Suspense boundaries
- Optimize database queries (use Drizzle efficiently)

## Security
- Validate all inputs with Zod
- Sanitize user inputs
- Use parameterized queries (Drizzle handles this)
- Implement proper authentication checks
- Rate limit API endpoints
- Hash API keys properly

## Error Handling
- Use error boundaries for React components
- Implement proper error pages (404, 500)
- Log errors appropriately
- Show user-friendly error messages
- Never expose sensitive information in errors

## File Management
- **Keep files modular**: Never exceed 400-500 lines per file
- Split large files into smaller, focused modules
- Use composition and separation of concerns
- Create reusable utilities and components
- One responsibility per file/component

## Documentation
- **Minimize .md files**: Avoid creating too many markdown documentation files
- Only create essential documentation (README.md)
- Keep documentation concise and focused
- Prefer inline code comments over separate documentation files
- Don't create multiple status/tracking .md files
- **Important Reference Documents** (located in `docs/` folder, not committed):
  - `docs/PLAN.md` - Main implementation plan and status (keep updated with all developments)
  - `docs/plan/CHANGELOG.md` - Detailed development changelog
  - `docs/plan/ROADMAP.md` - Future development roadmap
  - `docs/plan/INTEGRATIONS.md` - Integration roadmap (CLI, SDKs, plugins, inspired by Tolgee)
  - `docs/Agents.md` - AI agents and automation integration guide
  - `docs/GAP_ANALYSIS.md` - Feature gap analysis
  - `docs/UX_FLOWS.md` - End-to-end UX flow documentation
  - `docs/REQUIRED_KEYS.md` - Environment variables and API key setup
- **Always update `docs/PLAN.md`** when implementing new features or making significant changes
- When implementing agent integrations or API features, refer to `docs/Agents.md` for patterns and examples
- If PLAN.md becomes too large, break it into multiple files in `docs/plan/` folder

## Security & Git
- **NEVER commit sensitive information**:
  - API keys, secrets, passwords
  - Database credentials
  - Private keys
  - Environment variables with real values
  - User data or personal information
- Always use environment variables for sensitive data
- Check .gitignore before committing
- Review diffs before pushing
- **Never commit .md files** except README.md:
  - Don't commit status files, analysis files, or documentation files
  - Only README.md should be committed
  - Use .gitignore to exclude other .md files

